    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kinda yellow and pale compared to the top ones. what's probably going on with them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic sign of **nutrient deficiency**, specifically nitrogen, which is often the first thing to go when your tomato plants are stressed or the soil isn't balanced. The yellowing at the bottom is a big clue because nitrogen is mobile; the plant moves it from the older leaves to the new growth at the top to keep the fruit and new leaves healthy. It's a very efficient survival strategy, but it leaves your bottom leaves looking pale and tired.\n\nYou might want to consider a side-dressing of compost or a balanced fertilizer to replenish those nutrients, but before you rush out to the store, check if your plants are getting enough water. Sometimes, just like a mischievous goblin hiding in the corner of a room, a lack of water can cause leaves to wilt and turn yellow, mimicking nutrient issues. If you've been watering them deeply and consistently, then it's almost certainly a nutrient problem.\n\nHowever, if you've been over-fertilizing with too much nitrogen recently, that can actually cause the leaves to turn yellow while the stems get leggy and weak. It's a bit like a goblin who eats too much sugar and starts acting sluggish; the plant is trying to rebalance its internal",
      "source": "target",
